<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-completeness-axiom" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Completeness Axiom</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      This section develops the
      <term>completeness axiom</term><idx><h>completeness axiom</h></idx>
      for <m>\R</m> and a few standard consequences.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-completeness-axiom-statement">
    <title>Least Upper Bound Property</title>

    <p>
      The real numbers satisfy the following axiom.
    </p>

    <axiom xml:id="ax-least-upper-bound-property">
      <title>Least Upper Bound Property</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every non-empty subset of <m>\R</m> that is bounded above has a
          supremum in <m>\R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </axiom>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-completeness-infimum-equivalent">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The least upper bound property is equivalent to:
          every non-empty subset of <m>\R</m> that is bounded below has an
          infimum in <m>\R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Assume the least upper bound property. Let <m>A\subseteq\R</m> be
          non-empty and bounded below. Then <m>-A</m> is non-empty and bounded
          above, so <m>s:=\sup(-A)</m> exists. We claim <m>-s=\inf A</m>.
          For <m>a\in A</m>, we have <m>-a\in -A</m>, hence <m>-a\le s</m>,
          so <m>-s\le a</m>. Thus <m>-s</m> is a lower bound of <m>A</m>.
          If <m>l</m> is any lower bound of <m>A</m>, then <m>-l</m> is an upper
          bound of <m>-A</m>, so <m>s\le -l</m>, i.e. <m>l\le -s</m>. Therefore
          <m>-s</m> is the greatest lower bound of <m>A</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Conversely, assume every non-empty bounded-below subset of <m>\R</m>
          has an infimum. Let <m>B\subseteq\R</m> be non-empty and bounded above.
          Then <m>-B</m> is non-empty and bounded below, so <m>m:=\inf(-B)</m>
          exists. The same argument shows <m>-m=\sup B</m>. Hence the least
          upper bound property holds.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-sec-completeness-sup-monotone">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>\emptyset\ne A\subseteq B\subseteq\R</m> and
            <m>B</m> is bounded above. Prove <m>\sup A\le\sup B</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-completeness-consequences">
    <title>Consequences</title>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-n-unbounded-above">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The set <m>\N</m> is not bounded above in <m>\R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>\N</m> were bounded above. By the least upper bound
          property, <m>u:=\sup\N</m> exists. Since <m>u-1&lt;u</m>, the number
          <m>u-1</m> cannot be an upper bound of <m>\N</m>. So there is
          <m>n\in\N</m> with <m>u-1&lt;n</m>. Then <m>u&lt;n+1</m>, and
          <m>n+1\in\N</m>, contradicting that <m>u</m> is an upper bound.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-positive-square-root-existence">
      <title>Existence of Positive Square Roots</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For each <m>a&gt;0</m>, there exists a unique <m>u&gt;0</m> such that
          <m>u^2=a</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Uniqueness is immediate because <m>x\mapsto x^2</m> is strictly
          increasing on <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          For existence, define
          <m>S=\{x\in\R : x&gt;0,\ x^2\le a\}</m>. The set is non-empty:
          if <m>a\ge 1</m>, then <m>1\in S</m>; if <m>0&lt;a&lt;1</m>, then
          <m>a\in S</m>. It is bounded above by <m>M=\max\{a,1\}</m>, since
          <m>x&gt;M</m> implies <m>x^2&gt;a</m>. By completeness, <m>u:=\sup S</m>
          exists.
        </p>

        <p>
          If <m>u^2&lt;a</m>, then for sufficiently small <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>,
          we still have <m>(u+\varepsilon)^2\le a</m>, so <m>u+\varepsilon\in S</m>,
          contradicting that <m>u</m> is an upper bound of <m>S</m>. If
          <m>u^2&gt;a</m>, then for sufficiently small <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>,
          <m>(u-\varepsilon)^2&gt;a</m>; then every <m>x\in S</m> satisfies
          <m>x\le u-\varepsilon</m>, so <m>u-\varepsilon</m> is an upper bound
          of <m>S</m>, contradicting leastness of <m>u</m>. Hence
          <m>u^2=a</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      A standard comparison example is the ordered field
      <m>\Q</m>: the set <m>\{q\in\Q:q&gt;0,\ q^2&lt;2\}</m> is non-empty and bounded
      above in <m>\Q</m>, but it has no supremum in <m>\Q</m>. So <m>\Q</m> does
      not satisfy the least upper bound property.
    </p>
  </subsection>

</section>
